11
00:00:26,089 --> 00:00:28,599
It was not that he felt any emotion akin to

12
00:00:28,599 --> 00:00:30,179
love for Irene Adler.

13
00:00:31,150 --> 00:00:34,060
All emotions, and that one particularly,

14
00:00:34,060 --> 00:00:37,040
were abhorrent to his cold, precise but

15
00:00:37,039 --> 00:00:38,439
admirably balanced mind.

16
00:00:39,190 --> 00:00:41,270
He was, I take it, the most perfect

17
00:00:41,270 --> 00:00:43,220
reasoning and observing machine that the

18
00:00:43,219 --> 00:00:46,459
world has seen, but as a lover he would

19
00:00:46,460 --> 00:00:48,540
have placed himself in a false position.

20
00:00:49,300 --> 00:00:51,920
He never spoke of the softer passions, save

21
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:54,150
with a gibe and a sneer.

22
00:00:54,149 --> 00:00:56,049
They were admirable things for the

23
00:00:56,050 --> 00:00:58,250
observer--excellent for drawing the veil

24
00:00:58,250 --> 00:01:00,530
from men's motives and actions.

25
00:01:00,530 --> 00:01:02,730
But for the trained reasoner to admit such

26
00:01:02,730 --> 00:01:05,530
intrusions into his own delicate and finely

27
00:01:05,530 --> 00:01:08,270
adjusted temperament was to introduce a

28
00:01:08,270 --> 00:01:10,680
distracting factor which might throw a

29
00:01:10,680 --> 00:01:13,520
doubt upon all his mental results.

30
00:01:13,520 --> 00:01:16,270
Grit in a sensitive instrument, or a crack

31
00:01:16,270 --> 00:01:19,050
in one of his own high-power lenses, would

32
00:01:19,050 --> 00:01:20,940
not be more disturbing than a strong

33
00:01:20,940 --> 00:01:22,750
emotion in a nature such as his.

34
00:01:23,890 --> 00:01:27,030
And yet there was but one woman to him, and

35
00:01:27,030 --> 00:01:29,660
that woman was the late Irene Adler, of

36
00:01:29,660 --> 00:01:32,830
dubious and questionable memory.

37
00:01:32,830 --> 00:01:34,780
I had seen little of Holmes lately.

38
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:37,860
My marriage had drifted us away from each

39
00:01:37,860 --> 00:01:38,110
other.

40
00:01:38,750 --> 00:01:40,900
My own complete happiness, and the home-

41
00:01:40,900 --> 00:01:43,640
centred interests which rise up around the

42
00:01:43,640 --> 00:01:46,150
man who first finds himself master of his

43
00:01:46,150 --> 00:01:48,590
own establishment, were sufficient to

44
00:01:48,590 --> 00:01:52,240
absorb all my attention, while Holmes, who

45
00:01:52,240 --> 00:01:54,490
loathed every form of society with his

46
00:01:54,490 --> 00:01:57,420
whole Bohemian soul, remained in our

47
00:01:57,420 --> 00:02:00,130
lodgings in Baker Street, buried among his

48
00:02:00,130 --> 00:02:02,910
old books, and alternating from week to

49
00:02:02,910 --> 00:02:05,920
week between cocaine and ambition, the

50
00:02:05,920 --> 00:02:08,200
drowsiness of the drug, and the fierce

51
00:02:08,200 --> 00:02:10,060
energy of his own keen nature.

52
00:02:11,069 --> 00:02:14,349
He was still, as ever, deeply attracted by

53
00:02:14,349 --> 00:02:17,529
the study of crime, and occupied his

54
00:02:17,530 --> 00:02:20,590
immense faculties and extraordinary powers

55
00:02:20,590 --> 00:02:23,090
of observation in following out those

56
00:02:23,090 --> 00:02:25,820
clues, and clearing up those mysteries

57
00:02:25,819 --> 00:02:28,079
which had been abandoned as hopeless by the

58
00:02:28,079 --> 00:02:28,959
official police.

59
00:02:30,310 --> 00:02:32,920
From time to time I heard some vague

60
00:02:32,920 --> 00:02:35,490
account of his doings: of his summons to

61
00:02:35,489 --> 00:02:38,859
Odessa in the case of the Trepoff murder,

62
00:02:38,859 --> 00:02:40,879
of his clearing up of the singular tragedy

63
00:02:40,879 --> 00:02:44,389
of the Atkinson brothers at Trincomalee,

64
00:02:44,390 --> 00:02:46,520
and finally of the mission which he had

65
00:02:46,519 --> 00:02:49,109
accomplished so delicately and successfully

66
00:02:49,109 --> 00:02:51,179
for the reigning family of Holland.

67
00:02:51,180 --> 00:02:54,100
Beyond these signs of his activity,

68
00:02:54,099 --> 00:02:56,589
however, which I merely shared with all the

69
00:02:56,590 --> 00:02:59,430
readers of the daily press, I knew little

70
00:02:59,430 --> 00:03:01,390
of my former friend and companion.

71
00:03:02,439 --> 00:03:04,679
One night--it was on the twentieth of

72
00:03:04,680 --> 00:03:08,500
March, 1888--I was returning from a journey

73
00:03:08,499 --> 00:03:11,039
to a patient (for I had now returned to

74
00:03:11,040 --> 00:03:13,840
civil practice), when my way led me through

75
00:03:13,840 --> 00:03:15,240
Baker Street.

76
00:03:15,239 --> 00:03:18,219
As I passed the well-remembered door, which

77
00:03:18,219 --> 00:03:20,919
must always be associated in my mind with

78
00:03:20,920 --> 00:03:23,560
my wooing, and with the dark incidents of

79
00:03:23,560 --> 00:03:26,630
the Study in Scarlet, I was seized with a

80
00:03:26,629 --> 00:03:29,619
keen desire to see Holmes again, and to

81
00:03:29,620 --> 00:03:32,210
know how he was employing his extraordinary

82
00:03:32,209 --> 00:03:33,079
powers.

83
00:03:33,079 --> 00:03:35,939
His rooms were brilliantly lit, and, even

84
00:03:35,939 --> 00:03:39,469
as I looked up, I saw his tall, spare

85
00:03:39,469 --> 00:03:41,789
figure pass twice in a dark silhouette

86
00:03:41,790 --> 00:03:42,630
against the blind.

87
00:03:43,529 --> 00:03:46,569
He was pacing the room swiftly, eagerly,

88
00:03:46,569 --> 00:03:49,049
with his head sunk upon his chest and his

89
00:03:49,049 --> 00:03:50,579
hands clasped behind him.

90
00:03:51,450 --> 00:03:55,050
To me, who knew his every mood and habit,

91
00:03:55,049 --> 00:03:57,219
his attitude and manner told their own

92
00:03:57,219 --> 00:03:58,309
story.

93
00:03:58,310 --> 00:03:59,940
He was at work again.

94
00:04:00,870 --> 00:04:03,270
He had risen out of his drug-created dreams

95
00:04:03,269 --> 00:04:05,539
and was hot upon the scent of some new

96
00:04:05,540 --> 00:04:05,940
problem.

97
00:04:06,819 --> 00:04:08,859
I rang the bell and was shown up to the

98
00:04:08,859 --> 00:04:11,819
chamber which had formerly been in part my

99
00:04:11,819 --> 00:04:12,309
own.

100
00:04:12,310 --> 00:04:14,770
His manner was not effusive.

101
00:04:14,769 --> 00:04:17,769
It seldom was; but he was glad, I think, to

102
00:04:17,769 --> 00:04:18,159
see me.

103
00:04:18,419 --> 00:04:21,759
With hardly a word spoken, but with a

104
00:04:21,760 --> 00:04:24,440
kindly eye, he waved me to an armchair,

105
00:04:24,440 --> 00:04:27,160
threw across his case of cigars, and

106
00:04:27,160 --> 00:04:29,980
indicated a spirit case and a gasogene in

107
00:04:29,980 --> 00:04:31,310
the corner.

108
00:04:31,310 --> 00:04:33,540
Then he stood before the fire and looked me

109
00:04:33,540 --> 00:04:38,170
over in his singular introspective fashion.

110
00:04:38,170 --> 00:04:40,880
"Wedlock suits you," he remarked.

111
00:04:40,880 --> 00:04:43,700
"I think, Watson, that you have put on

112
00:04:43,700 --> 00:04:46,890
seven and a half pounds since I saw you."

113
00:04:46,890 --> 00:04:47,890
"Seven!"

114
00:04:47,890 --> 00:04:49,480
I answered.

115
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:51,390
"Indeed, I should have thought a little

116
00:04:51,390 --> 00:04:52,380
more.

117
00:04:52,380 --> 00:04:55,190
Just a trifle more, I fancy, Watson.

118
00:04:55,190 --> 00:04:58,040
And in practice again, I observe.

119
00:04:58,040 --> 00:05:00,350
You did not tell me that you intended to go

120
00:05:00,350 --> 00:05:01,890
into harness."

121
00:05:01,890 --> 00:05:04,700
"Then, how do you know?"

122
00:05:04,700 --> 00:05:07,160
"I see it, I deduce it.

123
00:05:07,160 --> 00:05:09,130
How do I know that you have been getting

124
00:05:09,130 --> 00:05:11,390
yourself very wet lately, and that you have

125
00:05:11,390 --> 00:05:15,440
a most clumsy and careless servant girl?"

126
00:05:15,440 --> 00:05:18,690
"My dear Holmes," said I, "this is too

127
00:05:18,690 --> 00:05:19,720
much.

128
00:05:19,720 --> 00:05:22,420
You would certainly have been burned, had

129
00:05:22,420 --> 00:05:23,390
you lived a few centuries ago.

130
00:05:24,530 --> 00:05:27,010
It is true that I had a country walk on

131
00:05:27,010 --> 00:05:30,310
Thursday and came home in a dreadful mess,

132
00:05:30,310 --> 00:05:33,400
but as I have changed my clothes I can't

133
00:05:33,400 --> 00:05:34,430
imagine how you deduce it.

134
00:05:35,310 --> 00:05:38,470
As to Mary Jane, she is incorrigible, and

135
00:05:38,470 --> 00:05:40,720
my wife has given her notice, but there,

136
00:05:40,720 --> 00:05:45,440
again, I fail to see how you work it out."

137
00:05:45,440 --> 00:05:47,500
He chuckled to himself and rubbed his long,

138
00:05:47,500 --> 00:05:50,060
nervous hands together.

139
00:05:50,060 --> 00:05:53,400
"It is simplicity itself," said he; "my

140
00:05:53,400 --> 00:05:55,670
eyes tell me that on the inside of your

141
00:05:55,670 --> 00:05:58,400
left shoe, just where the firelight strikes

142
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:01,660
it, the leather is scored by six almost

143
00:06:01,660 --> 00:06:03,320
parallel cuts.

144
00:06:03,320 --> 00:06:05,720
Obviously they have been caused by someone

145
00:06:05,720 --> 00:06:07,960
who has very carelessly scraped round the

146
00:06:07,960 --> 00:06:10,260
edges of the sole in order to remove

147
00:06:10,260 --> 00:06:11,450
crusted mud from it.

148
00:06:12,280 --> 00:06:14,980
Hence, you see, my double deduction that

149
00:06:14,980 --> 00:06:17,760
you had been out in vile weather, and that

150
00:06:17,760 --> 00:06:20,210
you had a particularly malignant boot-

151
00:06:20,210 --> 00:06:22,650
slitting specimen of the London slavey.

152
00:06:23,750 --> 00:06:26,410
As to your practice, if a gentleman walks

153
00:06:26,410 --> 00:06:29,620
into my rooms smelling of iodoform, with a

154
00:06:29,620 --> 00:06:32,020
black mark of nitrate of silver upon his

155
00:06:32,020 --> 00:06:35,380
right forefinger, and a bulge on the right

156
00:06:35,380 --> 00:06:37,800
side of his top-hat to show where he has

157
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:40,690
secreted his stethoscope, I must be dull,

158
00:06:40,690 --> 00:06:44,620
indeed, if I do not pronounce him to be an

159
00:06:44,620 --> 00:06:46,450
active member of the medical profession."

160
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,370
I could not help laughing at the ease with

161
00:06:50,370 --> 00:06:52,240
which he explained his process of

162
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:52,750
deduction.

163
00:06:52,750 --> 00:06:56,970
"When I hear you give your reasons," I

164
00:06:56,970 --> 00:06:59,730
remarked, "the thing always appears to me

165
00:06:59,730 --> 00:07:02,570
to be so ridiculously simple that I could

166
00:07:02,570 --> 00:07:05,570
easily do it myself, though at each

167
00:07:05,570 --> 00:07:07,970
successive instance of your reasoning I am

168
00:07:07,970 --> 00:07:10,060
baffled until you explain your process.

169
00:07:10,060 --> 00:07:12,900
And yet I believe that my eyes are as good

170
00:07:12,900 --> 00:07:13,460
as yours."

171
00:07:14,520 --> 00:07:16,920
"Quite so," he answered, lighting a

172
00:07:16,920 --> 00:07:19,380
cigarette, and throwing himself down into

173
00:07:19,380 --> 00:07:21,050
an armchair.

174
00:07:21,050 --> 00:07:23,870
"You see, but you do not observe.

175
00:07:23,870 --> 00:07:25,670
The distinction is clear.

176
00:07:25,670 --> 00:07:28,280
For example, you have frequently seen the

177
00:07:28,280 --> 00:07:30,310
steps which lead up from the hall to this

178
00:07:30,310 --> 00:07:31,620
room."

179
00:07:31,620 --> 00:07:33,280
"Frequently."

180
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:34,940
"How often?"

181
00:07:34,940 --> 00:07:38,860
"Well, some hundreds of times."

182
00:07:38,860 --> 00:07:41,430
"Then how many are there?"

183
00:07:41,430 --> 00:07:42,680
"How many?

184
00:07:42,680 --> 00:07:44,700
I don't know."

185
00:07:44,700 --> 00:07:46,150
"Quite so!

186
00:07:46,150 --> 00:07:47,840
You have not observed.

187
00:07:47,840 --> 00:07:49,490
And yet you have seen.

188
00:07:49,490 --> 00:07:51,320
That is just my point.

189
00:07:51,320 --> 00:07:54,680
Now, I know that there are seventeen steps,

190
00:07:54,680 --> 00:07:57,640
because I have both seen and observed.

191
00:07:57,640 --> 00:08:00,050
By-the-way, since you are interested in

192
00:08:00,050 --> 00:08:02,190
these little problems, and since you are

193
00:08:02,190 --> 00:08:04,390
good enough to chronicle one or two of my

194
00:08:04,390 --> 00:08:07,480
trifling experiences, you may be interested

195
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:09,650
in this."

196
00:08:09,650 --> 00:08:12,020
He threw over a sheet of thick, pink-tinted

197
00:08:12,020 --> 00:08:14,180
note-paper which had been lying open upon

198
00:08:14,180 --> 00:08:15,620
the table.

199
00:08:15,620 --> 00:08:18,810
"It came by the last post," said he.

200
00:08:18,810 --> 00:08:21,020
"Read it aloud."

201
00:08:21,020 --> 00:08:23,220
The note was undated, and without either

202
00:08:23,220 --> 00:08:24,600
signature or address.

203
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:29,100
"There will call upon you to-night, at a

204
00:08:29,100 --> 00:08:32,370
quarter to eight o'clock," it said, "a

205
00:08:32,370 --> 00:08:35,200
gentleman who desires to consult you upon a

206
00:08:35,199 --> 00:08:37,259
matter of the very deepest moment.

207
00:08:38,159 --> 00:08:40,579
Your recent services to one of the royal

208
00:08:40,579 --> 00:08:42,669
houses of Europe have shown that you are

209
00:08:42,669 --> 00:08:45,599
one who may safely be trusted with matters

210
00:08:45,600 --> 00:08:48,440
which are of an importance which can hardly

211
00:08:48,439 --> 00:08:50,249
be exaggerated.

212
00:08:50,249 --> 00:08:52,229
This account of you we have from all

213
00:08:52,230 --> 00:08:53,960
quarters received.

214
00:08:53,959 --> 00:08:56,969
Be in your chamber then at that hour, and

215
00:08:56,970 --> 00:08:59,600
do not take it amiss if your visitor wear a

216
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:00,850
mask."

217
00:09:00,850 --> 00:09:05,290
"This is indeed a mystery," I remarked.

218
00:09:05,290 --> 00:09:08,280
"What do you imagine that it means?"

219
00:09:08,279 --> 00:09:10,519
"I have no data yet.

220
00:09:10,519 --> 00:09:13,139
It is a capital mistake to theorize before

221
00:09:13,139 --> 00:09:15,089
one has data.

222
00:09:15,089 --> 00:09:17,559
Insensibly one begins to twist facts to

223
00:09:17,560 --> 00:09:20,350
suit theories, instead of theories to suit

224
00:09:20,350 --> 00:09:21,420
facts.

225
00:09:21,420 --> 00:09:23,140
But the note itself.

226
00:09:23,139 --> 00:09:25,919
What do you deduce from it?"

227
00:09:25,920 --> 00:09:28,670
I carefully examined the writing, and the

228
00:09:28,670 --> 00:09:31,700
paper upon which it was written.

229
00:09:31,699 --> 00:09:34,389
"The man who wrote it was presumably well

230
00:09:34,389 --> 00:09:37,619
to do," I remarked, endeavouring to imitate

231
00:09:37,620 --> 00:09:39,800
my companion's processes.

232
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:42,030
"Such paper could not be bought under half

233
00:09:42,029 --> 00:09:43,639
a crown a packet.

234
00:09:43,639 --> 00:09:45,769
It is peculiarly strong and stiff."

235
00:09:45,769 --> 00:09:50,669
"Peculiar--that is the very word," said

236
00:09:50,670 --> 00:09:51,450
Holmes.

237
00:09:51,449 --> 00:09:54,019
"It is not an English paper at all.

238
00:09:54,019 --> 00:09:56,339
Hold it up to the light."

239
00:09:56,339 --> 00:10:00,049
I did so, and saw a large "E" with a small

240
00:10:00,050 --> 00:10:05,130
"g," a "P," and a large "G" with a small

241
00:10:05,129 --> 00:10:09,409
"t" woven into the texture of the paper.

242
00:10:09,410 --> 00:10:13,060
"What do you make of that?" asked Holmes.

243
00:10:13,059 --> 00:10:16,529
"The name of the maker, no doubt; or his

244
00:10:16,529 --> 00:10:18,079
monogram, rather."

245
00:10:18,079 --> 00:10:18,699
"Not at all.

246
00:10:18,699 --> 00:10:21,619
The 'G' with the small 't' stands for

247
00:10:21,620 --> 00:10:24,070
'Gesellschaft,' which is the German for

248
00:10:24,069 --> 00:10:25,309
'Company.'

249
00:10:25,309 --> 00:10:27,469
It is a customary contraction like our

250
00:10:27,470 --> 00:10:29,880
'Co.'

251
00:10:29,879 --> 00:10:32,799
'P,' of course, stands for 'Papier.'

252
00:10:32,800 --> 00:10:34,920
Now for the 'Eg.'

253
00:10:34,920 --> 00:10:36,660
Let us glance at our Continental

254
00:10:36,660 --> 00:10:37,280
Gazetteer."

255
00:10:38,670 --> 00:10:40,720
He took down a heavy brown volume from his

256
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:42,270
shelves.

257
00:10:42,269 --> 00:10:47,229
"Eglow, Eglonitz--here we are, Egria.

258
00:10:47,230 --> 00:10:50,580
It is in a German-speaking country--in

259
00:10:50,579 --> 00:10:52,819
Bohemia, not far from Carlsbad.

260
00:10:52,819 --> 00:10:55,209
'Remarkable as being the scene of the death

261
00:10:55,209 --> 00:10:58,889
of Wallenstein, and for its numerous glass-

262
00:10:58,889 --> 00:11:01,059
factories and paper-mills.'

263
00:11:01,059 --> 00:11:03,369
Ha, ha, my boy, what do you make of that?"

264
00:11:04,389 --> 00:11:06,649
His eyes sparkled, and he sent up a great

265
00:11:06,649 --> 00:11:08,789
blue triumphant cloud from his cigarette.

266
00:11:08,790 --> 00:11:13,860
"The paper was made in Bohemia," I said.

267
00:11:13,860 --> 00:11:15,160
"Precisely.

268
00:11:15,160 --> 00:11:18,570
And the man who wrote the note is a German.

269
00:11:18,569 --> 00:11:20,909
Do you note the peculiar construction of

270
00:11:20,910 --> 00:11:23,750
the sentence--'This account of you we have

